<h2>Current Malaria Research</h2>
<div class="paragraph" style="text-align:left;">
  <p><i>Malaria research employs cutting edge tools and techniques from genetic engineering, evolutionary biology, epidemiology and disease modeling. No matter what your interests you can contribute towards the eradication of Malaria. Here are some of 2015's breakthroughs:</i></p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Genetic engineers in UC Irvine break Mendels laws, creating a CRISPR Cas9 based gene drive system that has the potential to deliver resistance to the malaria parasite to every a Mosquito in the world within a single breeding season.
      <br />
      <a target="_blank" href="http://www.pnas.org/content/early/2015/11/18/1521077112.abstract">http://www.pnas.org/content/early/2015/11/18/1521077112.abstract</a>
    </li>
    <li>
      This is a breakdown of the effectiveness and relative impact of bed nets, antimalarial drugs and insecticides during the Roll Back Malaria partnership, which ran from 2000-2015. This important analysis will inform the future distribution of resources in the on going fight against malaria.
      <br />
      <a target="_blank" href="http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v526/n7572/full/nature15535.html">http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v526/n7572/full/nature15535.html</a>
    </li>
    <li>The malaria parasite can now be detected using an app and an attachment to your mobile device. Check out how these researchers at Texas A&amp;M University combined microscopy, imaging and programming in the fight against malaria
